snippet.textDisplay:
All manufacturers have collision repair procedures outlining specifically how to replace structural components. The objective is to bring the damaged vehicle back to PAC =Pre Accident Condition. For safety and liability reasons once vehicle is returned to the streets, these are areas you just don't want to ignore. Damage estimating systems like CCC1 or Mitchell will outline if entire rocker or frame rail must be replaced or if it can be spliced in. Once you deviate from that procedure you are basically re-engineering the vehicle crash performance capabilities. In laymen terms, you are responsible in a court of law if occupants are injured and it is determined you failed to follow procedures to the letter. There is a case in Michigan where the dealer did not replace the roof properly on a vehicle and it was in another crash. It ended up with a multi million dollar judgement against the body shop. Having worked heavy collision since the early 70's lots of things have changed.
Everyone is rushing to the lawyers hoping for a huge verdict to cash in. Just be aware that visually acceptable repairs are one thing. Safe and legal repairs are a whole other animal. Good luck.
